# {{ pkgScope }}/{{ name }}

This package exposes a simple TypeScript API backed by a Go-based Node-API addon.

- The Go package is built as a C archive in `libs/{{ name }}-go` and linked by a tiny C N-API shim in `libs/{{ name }}-native` to produce a `.node` addon.
- The native addon is copied here to `native/{{ addon_name }}.node`.
- The TypeScript entry loads the addon from a stable relative path using `createRequire(import.meta.url)`.

## Quickstart

Follow these steps to scaffold, build, and test the addon-backed library:

1) Generate the scaffold (already done if you are reading this in a generated repo):

   - `scaf new node go-addon {{ name }} --yes`

2) Build the Go c-archive and the Node-API addon via Buck/Nix:

   - `buck2 build //libs/{{ name }}-go:carchive`
   - `buck2 build //libs/{{ name }}-native:napi_addon`

3) Ensure glue is present (export graph → sync providers (Node, if lockfiles exist) → auto_map):

   - `node tools/buck/export-graph.ts --out tools/buck/graph.json`
   - `node tools/buck/sync-providers-node.ts` (no-op if no pnpm lockfiles are present)
   - `node tools/buck/gen-auto-map.ts --graph tools/buck/graph.json --out third_party/providers/auto_map.bzl`

4) Run the Node unit test (single test file, per project conventions):

   - `buck2 test //libs/{{ name }}:unit`

## Runtime loading behavior

- The compiled addon is made available at a stable path: `native/{{ addon_name }}.node`.
- The loader respects an override for diagnostics: set `ADDON_PATH=/absolute/path/to/{{ addon_name }}.node` to force a specific binary at runtime (useful for low-friction experiments).

